"Rivalan P., Barbraud C., Inchausti P., Weimerskirch H.","Combined impacts of longline fisheries and climate on the persistence of the Amsterdam Albatross Diomedia amsterdamensis",2010,"Ibis","152","1",,"6","18",,,10.1111/j.1474-919X.2009.00977.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-71949129286&partnerID=40&md5=218462637628c04ab2ddcb62cfc2da40","Centre d'Etudes Biologiques de Chizé, Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique (UPR 1934), 79360 Villiers en Bois, France","Rivalan, P., Centre d'Etudes Biologiques de Chizé, Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique (UPR 1934), 79360 Villiers en Bois, France; Barbraud, C., Centre d'Etudes Biologiques de Chizé, Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique (UPR 1934), 79360 Villiers en Bois, France; Inchausti, P., Centre d'Etudes Biologiques de Chizé, Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique (UPR 1934), 79360 Villiers en Bois, France; Weimerskirch, H., Centre d'Etudes Biologiques de Chizé, Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique (UPR 1934), 79360 Villiers en Bois, France","Incidental capture of seabirds in longline fishing gear is a central issue in the conservation of many long-lived marine species. Despite growing evidence of climate-induced effects on population trends of long-lived species, climate change remains generally overlooked in most risk assessments of seabirds. Because variation in climate may interact with the detrimental effects of bycatch, considering climate is of great importance, especially in the context of ongoing global warming. This paper examines the combined effects of bycatch and climate change on the persistence of one of the world's rarest birds, the Amsterdam Albatross Diomedea amsterdamensis, which has a single population in the upland plateau of Amsterdam Island (Southeast Indian Ocean). Using continuous monitoring from 1983 onwards, we first estimated the relationship between climate and the species' demographic parameters. We then built a stochastic matrix population model to estimate the population growth rate and the probability that the population declines below the level recorded in 1983 of nine breeding pairs under different scenarios involving the joint effects of additional mortality caused by longline fisheries and climate change. The results suggest that the demography of the Amsterdam Albatross is influenced by climate in both breeding and wintering grounds and that these relationships may to some extent compensate for the impact of additive bycatch mortality. However, these compensatory effects would be negligible if the annual additional mortality exceeds around six individuals per year, suggesting that the resumption of longline fishery in the foraging range of the Amsterdam Albatross would rapidly put this species at risk of extinction. © 2009 British Ornithologists' Union.","Diomedea amsterdamensis; Fishing effort; Indian Ocean Dipole; Multistate capture-recapture models; Stochastic matrix models","bycatch; climate change; climate effect; extinction risk; fishing effort; fishing gear; longlining; mark-recapture method; mortality; persistence; population decline; population modeling; rare species; risk assessment; seabird; stochasticity; Amsterdam Island; French Southern Territories; Indian Ocean; Indian Ocean islands; Aves; Diomedea amsterdamensis",,,,,,"Achutarao, K.M., Sperber, K.R., ENSO simulation in coupled ocean-atmosphere models: Are the current models better? (2006) Clim. Dynam., 27, pp. 1-15; Aebischer, N.J., Coulson, J.C., Colebrook, J.M., Parallel long-term trends across four marine trophic levels and weather (1990) Nature, 347, pp. 753-755; Akçakaya, H.R., A method for simulating demographic stochasticity (1991) Ecol. Model., 54, pp. 133-136; Arnold, J.M., Brault, S., Croxall, J.P., Albatross population in peril: A population trajectory for black-browed albatross at South Georgia (2006) Ecol. Appl., 16, pp. 419-432; Barbraud, C., Weimerskirch, H., Contrasting effects of the extent of sea-ice on t